aVNow this gentleman, Isambard Kingdom Brunel,
p52
aVdesigned many great things in his career in the 19th century,
p53
aVincluding the Clifton suspension bridge in Bristol
p54
aVand the Thames tunnel at Rotherhithe.
p55
aVBoth great designs and actually very innovative too.
p56
aVHis greatest creation
p57
aVruns actually right through here in Oxford.
p58
aVIt's called the Great Western Railway.
p59
aa(lp60
VAnd as a kid I grew up very close to here,
p61
aVand one of my favorite things to do
p62
aVwas to cycle along by the side of the railway
p63
aVwaiting for the great big express trains to roar past.
p64
aVYou can see it represented here in J.M.W. Turner's painting,
p65
aV"Rain, Steam and Speed".
p66
aVNow, what Brunel said that he wanted to achieve for his passengers
p67
aVwas the experience of floating across the countryside.
p68
aa(lp69
VNow, this was back in the 19th century.
p70
aVAnd to do that meant creating the flattest gradients
p71
aVthat had ever yet been made,
p72
aVwhich meant building long viaducts across river valleys \u2014
p73
aVthis is actually the viaduct across the Thames at Maidenhead \u2014
p74
aVand long tunnels such as the one at Box, in Wiltshire.
p75
aVBut he didn't stop there. He didn't stop
p76
aVwith just trying to design the best railway journey.
p77
aVHe imagined an integrated transportation system
p78
aVin which it would be possible for a passenger to embark
p79
aVon a train in London
p80
aVand disembark from a ship in New York.
p81
aVOne journey from London to New York.
p82
aVThis is the S.S. Great Western that he built
p83
aVto take care of the second half of that journey.
