aa(lp85
VNow, Brunel was working 100 years before
p86
aVthe emergence of the design profession,
p87
aVbut I think he was using design thinking
p88
aVto solve problems and to create world-changing innovations.
p89
aVNow, design thinking begins with what Roger Martin,
p90
aVthe business school professor at the University of Toronto,
p91
aVcalls integrative thinking.
p92
aVAnd that's the ability to exploit opposing ideas
p93
aVand opposing constraints
p94
aVto create new solutions.
p95
aVIn the case of design, that means
p96
aVbalancing desirability, what humans need,
p97
aVwith technical feasibility,
p98
aVand economic viability.
p99
aVWith innovations like the Great Western,
p100
aVwe can stretch that balance to the absolute limit.
p101
aa(lp102
VSo somehow, we went from this to this.
p103
aVSystems thinkers who were reinventing the world,
p104
aVto a priesthood of folks in black turtlenecks and designer glasses
p105
aVworking on small things.
p106
aVAs our industrial society matured,
p107
aVso design became a profession
p108
aVand it focused on an ever smaller canvas
p109
aVuntil it came to stand for aesthetics,
p110
aVimage and fashion.
p111
aVNow I'm not trying to throw stones here.
p112
aVI'm a fully paid-up member of that priesthood,
p113
aVand somewhere in here I have my designer glasses.
p114
aVThere we go.
p115
aVBut I do think that perhaps design
p116
aVis getting big again.
p117
aVAnd that's happening through
p118
aVthe application of design thinking
p119
aVto new kinds of problems \u2014
p120
aVto global warming, to education,
p121
aVhealthcare, security, clean water, whatever.
