aa(lp123
VAnd as we see this reemergence of design thinking
p124
aVand we see it beginning to tackle new kinds of problems,
p125
aVthere are some basic ideas that I think we can observe that are useful.
p126
aVAnd I'd like to talk about some of those
p127
aVjust for the next few minutes.
p128
aVThe first of those is that design is
p129
aVhuman-centered.
p130
aVIt may integrate technology and economics,
p131
aVbut it starts with what humans need, or might need.
p132
aVWhat makes life easier, more enjoyable?
p133
aVWhat makes technology useful and usable?
p134
aVBut that is more than simply good ergonomics,
p135
aVputting the buttons in the right place.
p136
aVIt's often about understanding culture and context
p137
aVbefore we even know where to start to have ideas.
p138
aa(lp139
VSo when a team was working on a new vision screening program in India,
p140
aVthey wanted to understand what the aspirations
p141
aVand motivations were of these school children
p142
aVto understand how they might play a role
p143
aVin screening their parents.
p144
aVConversion Sound has developed a high quality,
p145
aVultra-low-cost digital hearing aid
p146
aVfor the developing world.
p147
aVNow, in the West we rely on highly trained technicians
p148
aVto fit these hearing aids.
p149
aVIn places like India, those technicians simply don't exist.
p150
aVSo it took a team working in India
p151
aVwith patients and community health workers
p152
aVto understand how a PDA
p153
aVand an application on a PDA
p154
aVmight replace those technicians
p155
aVin a fitting and diagnostic service.
