aa(lp221
VSo William Beveridge, when he wrote the first of his famous reports in 1942,
p222
aVcreated what became Britain's welfare state
p223
aVin which he hoped that every citizen
p224
aVwould be an active participant
p225
aVin their own social well-being.
p226
aVBy the time he wrote his third report,
p227
aVhe confessed that he had failed
p228
aVand instead had created a society of welfare consumers.
p229
aa(lp230
VHilary Cottam, Charlie Leadbeater,
p231
aVand Hugo Manassei of Participle
p232
aVhave taken this idea of participation,
p233
aVand in their manifesto entitled Beveridge 4.0,
p234
aVthey are suggesting a framework
p235
aVfor reinventing the welfare state.
