aVSo these are just some of the kind of basic ideas
p273
aVaround design thinking
p274
aVand some of the new kinds of projects
p275
aVthat they're being applied to.
p276
aVBut I'd like to go back to Brunel here,
p277
aVand suggest a connection that might explain why this is happening now,
p278
aVand maybe why design thinking is a useful tool.
p279
aVAnd that connection is change.
p280
aVIn times of change we need
p281
aVnew alternatives, new ideas.
p282
aa(lp283
VNow, Brunel worked at the height of the Industrial Revolution,
p284
aVwhen all of life and our economy
p285
aVwas being reinvented.
p286
aVNow the industrial systems of Brunel's time have run their course,
p287
aVand indeed they are part of the problem today.
p288
aVBut, again, we are in the midst of massive change.
p289
aVAnd that change is forcing us to question
p290
aVquite fundamental aspects of our society \u2014
p291
aVhow we keep ourselves healthy, how we govern ourselves,
p292
aVhow we educate ourselves, how we keep ourselves secure.
p293
aVAnd in these times of change, we need these new choices
p294
aVbecause our existing solutions are simply becoming obsolete.
p295
aa(lp296
VSo why design thinking?
p297
aVBecause it gives us a new way of tackling problems.
p298
aVInstead of defaulting to our normal convergent approach
p299
aVwhere we make the best choice out of available alternatives,
p300
aVit encourages us to take a divergent approach,
p301
aVto explore new alternatives, new solutions,
p302
aVnew ideas that have not existed before.
